snippet: Greek political leaders appeared unable to break a deadlock left by inconclusive general elections last Sunday, suggesting that a second round of polls may be inevitable.
abstract: Greek political leaders appear unable to break deadlock left by inconclusive general elections, suggesting that second round of polls may be inevitable; many fear new round of elections will interfere with series of important deadlines set up by the bailout deal; apart from paying a bond that comes due in May, Greece must identify $14.8 billion in spending cuts for 2013 and 2014.

byline.original: By RACHEL DONADIO and NIKI KITSANTONIS

lead_paragraph: Greek political leaders appeared unable to break a deadlock left by inconclusive general elections last Sunday, suggesting that a second round of polls may be inevitable.

headline.seo: Impasse in Greece Could Force New Vote
headline.main: Election Impasse in Greece Could Force a New Vote
headline.print_headline: Election Impasse in Greece Could Force a New Vote
